226
00:16:02,895 --> 00:16:06,064
         to have covers         
  in order to keep out insects. 

227
00:16:10,036 --> 00:16:12,236
        these traditional       
       german beer steins,      

228
00:16:12,238 --> 00:16:14,906
with their ornate ceramic bodies
         and pewter lids        

229
00:16:14,908 --> 00:16:16,573
  are functional works of art.  

230
00:16:16,575 --> 00:16:19,310
        the word "stein"        
   is short for a german word   

231
00:16:19,312 --> 00:16:21,912
    meaning "stoneware jug."    

232
00:16:21,914 --> 00:16:24,515
        production begins       
    in the casting department   

233
00:16:24,517 --> 00:16:26,050
     with a plaster mold --     

234
00:16:26,052 --> 00:16:29,453
 its cavity the shape and design
      of the stein's body.      

235
00:16:29,455 --> 00:16:31,189
    they pour in liquid clay,   

236
00:16:31,191 --> 00:16:33,791
      wait about two hours      
       until it thickens,       

237
00:16:33,793 --> 00:16:36,394
          then pour out         
    whatever liquid remains.    

238
00:16:36,396 --> 00:16:39,730
  after testing the consistency 
     of what's still inside,    

239
00:16:39,732 --> 00:16:41,933
    they gingerly disassemble   
            the mold,           

240
00:16:41,935 --> 00:16:43,467
   revealing the stein's body.  

241
00:16:43,469 --> 00:16:46,137
    the mold has transferred    
    all the intricate detail    

242
00:16:46,139 --> 00:16:47,405
     to the clay's surface.     

243
00:16:50,276 --> 00:16:52,276
    for certain stein shapes,   

244
00:16:52,278 --> 00:16:55,546
     they get better results    
        using solid clay.       

245
00:16:55,548 --> 00:16:58,482
          they cut off          
      the amount they need,     

246
00:16:58,484 --> 00:17:02,153
          then drop it          
     inside a plaster mold.     

247
00:17:05,959 --> 00:17:07,691
    a machine pushes the clay   

248
00:17:07,693 --> 00:17:10,294
       into every crevice       
       of the mold cavity.      

249
00:17:10,296 --> 00:17:13,297
 a worker trims away any excess 
         that oozes out.        

250
00:17:13,299 --> 00:17:16,934
then the mold goes into a drying
     machine for 20 minutes.    

251
00:17:19,439 --> 00:17:20,838
       when it comes out,       

252
00:17:20,840 --> 00:17:24,075
  they disassemble the sections 
     to extract the casting.    

253
00:17:27,980 --> 00:17:30,247
    whether made from liquid    
         or solid clay,         

254
00:17:30,249 --> 00:17:32,517
      each stein body goes      
      on a potter's wheel       

255
00:17:32,519 --> 00:17:34,519
       for some refining.       

256
00:17:34,521 --> 00:17:35,987
    the potter removes seams    

257
00:17:35,989 --> 00:17:38,522
           that formed          
  where the mold sections met.  

258
00:17:38,524 --> 00:17:41,259
          he also trims         
    and smoothes out the rim.   

259
00:17:41,261 --> 00:17:44,061
    then, using some wet clay   
         as an adhesive,        

260
00:17:44,063 --> 00:17:45,863
  he attaches an ornate handle. 

261
00:17:45,865 --> 00:17:48,399
            it, too,            
    is made entirely of clay.   

262
00:17:48,401 --> 00:17:50,935
      the factory shapes it     
        either in a mold        

263
00:17:50,937 --> 00:17:52,537
    or with a dye in a press.   

264
00:17:52,539 --> 00:17:55,606
 finally, they stamp the bottom 
        with two marks --       

265
00:17:55,608 --> 00:17:59,410
        "made in germany"       
     and the company brand.     

266
00:17:59,412 --> 00:18:02,280
now the coloring process begins.

267
00:18:02,282 --> 00:18:05,749
  they coat the stein body with 
  special paint for ceramics -- 

268
00:18:05,751 --> 00:18:08,886
     first, a watery coat of    
 the background color all over, 

269
00:18:08,888 --> 00:18:12,190
   then a thicker coat around   
 the reliefs to highlight them. 

270
00:18:15,628 --> 00:18:18,696
   they rub most of the paint   
         off the reliefs        

271
00:18:18,698 --> 00:18:21,099
   to accentuate the contrast.  

272
00:18:21,101 --> 00:18:25,903
   next, workers spray a milky  
    glaze over the stein body   

273
00:18:25,905 --> 00:18:27,304
         inside and out.        

274
00:18:27,306 --> 00:18:30,707
    this glaze is made mainly   
     of sodium and silicon,     

275
00:18:30,709 --> 00:18:32,776
       minerals that turn       
     into transparent glass     

276
00:18:32,778 --> 00:18:34,111
        under high heat.        

277
00:18:34,113 --> 00:18:36,380
      this will strengthen      
  and waterproof the stoneware  

278
00:18:36,382 --> 00:18:39,116
           beneath it.          

279
00:18:39,118 --> 00:18:42,052
  workers load dozens of stein  
      bodies into an oven,      

280
00:18:42,054 --> 00:18:45,122
  where they bake at more than  
    2,000 degrees fahrenheit    

281
00:18:45,124 --> 00:18:46,323
          for 12 hours.         

282
00:18:46,325 --> 00:18:50,194
     this hardens the clay,     
    turns the colors vibrant,   

283
00:18:50,196 --> 00:18:55,399
    and transforms the glaze    
into a protective glass coating.

284
00:18:55,401 --> 00:18:59,670
 after a 12-hour cooling period,
    the true artistry begins.   

285
00:18:59,672 --> 00:19:02,874
        a skilled painter       
     embellishes the design     

286
00:19:02,876 --> 00:19:05,343
  with colorful enamel paints.  

287
00:19:25,165 --> 00:19:28,765
   a second firing, this time   
     for just 5 to 6 hours,     

288
00:19:28,767 --> 00:19:32,637
         bakes the paint        
     onto the glass surface.    

289
00:19:32,639 --> 00:19:36,107
     now, to top it all off,    
     the stein's ornate lid.    

290
00:19:36,109 --> 00:19:39,777
       it's made of pewter      
         cast in a mold.        

291
00:19:39,779 --> 00:19:42,580
  the thumb lift pivots the lid 
           on a hinge.          

292
00:19:42,582 --> 00:19:44,982
       to attach the lid        
       to the stein body,       

293
00:19:44,984 --> 00:19:47,184
  they position the thumb lift  
         on the handle,         

294
00:19:47,186 --> 00:19:50,087
          then assemble         
 a small mounting tool over it. 

295
00:19:52,925 --> 00:19:55,493
  they pour in molten pewter... 

296
00:19:58,130 --> 00:20:01,598
 ...then, after a minute or so, 
       remove the device.       

297
00:20:01,600 --> 00:20:04,068
     the pewter has hardened    
           into a ring          

298
00:20:04,070 --> 00:20:06,671
    attaching the thumb lift    
         to the handle.         

299
00:20:08,507 --> 00:20:13,311
    they clip off the excess,   
 then buff the metal to a shine.

300
00:20:20,353 --> 00:20:24,554
  with their traditional scenes 
  or more contemporary themes,  

301
00:20:24,556 --> 00:20:27,958
        these beer steins       
   are the toast of the town.   

